<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Pendragon rises 41% to Pounds 7.4m - New
car market showed recovery while used car prices firmed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stronger demand and improved margins helped Pendragon, the luxury and
executive car dealer, report a 41 per cent improvement in 1993.
Pre-tax profits rose to Pounds 7.37m, against Pounds 5.23m last time, on
turnover up 29 per cent to Pounds 276.4m (Pounds 214.6m), including Pounds
5.59m from acquisitions.
Earnings per share emerged at 14.1p (11.8p) out of which an increased final
dividend of 4.8p (4.4p) is being paid, raising the total for the year to
7.2p (6.6p). Despite the increase the shares closed 2p lower at 304p.
Mr Trevor Finn, chief executive, said: 'New and used car profits,
after-sales contributions and profits from the contract hire business, all
showed improved results in 1993.
Operating profits grew by 31 per cent to Pounds 8.99m (Pounds 6.87m). .
Interest costs were flat at Pounds 1.62m (Pounds 1.64m).
Buoyed by the general car market recovery, new car gross profits increased
to Pounds 11.7m (Pounds 9.1m). Similarly the increased availability of
nearly-new cars enabled the group to sell more used cars at higher margins.
Overall used car gross profits increased by 82 per cent from Pounds 2.3m to
Pounds 4.2m.
Firmer used car prices also helped lift the profitability of Pendragon's
contract hire business, which turned in a 73 per cent gain in profits to
Pounds 2.5m (Pounds 1.4m).
Meanwhile the contribution from parts, service and body-shop activities  -
the mainstay of profit growth throughout the recession - increased to Pounds
20.4m (Pounds 16.9m.)
The group ended the year with net debt of Pounds 8.2m (Pounds 8.8m)
representing gearing of 16 per cent.
COMMENT
Pendragon has used the proceeds of last year's Pounds 16.6m rights issue
wisely, and now has the largest grouping of executive and luxury car
franchises in the UK. Future growth is likely to come from adding franchises
to existing sites, somewhat greater representation in the volume segment of
the market and an expansion of the contract hire business. Meanwhile the
upturn in the UK luxury market lagged the general upturn so Pendragon should
see further benefits this year. Pre-tax profits of about Pounds 9.2m are
likely, pro-ducing earnings of 16.8p and a reasonable prospective p/e of
about 18.1.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Pendragon.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P5511 New and Used Car Dealers.
</IN>
