<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The extraordinary and fascinating thing about Italy's political situation is
that matters could so easily go either way: after all the quick change
governments since the second world war, the results of the impending
election could be total chaos and the virtual disintegration of the country
into northern, central and southern sectors - almost like the pattern in the
middle ages. Or the country could emerge with the most stable government of
the modern age. Assignment tries to answer the question 'Quo vadis Italy?'
(7.45 BBC2)
Torvill And Dean: Facing The Music is a documentary by Edward Mirzeoff that
follows the pair through their attempted comeback at the National
Championships, the European Championships, and finally the Olympics where,
if the tabloid media are to be believed, they were so scandalously robbed of
gold (8.00 BBC1).
40 Minutes is extended to 60 for its account of a year in the life of
Bronwen Vickers, the mother whose leg was blown off by some lunatic wanting
to further the aims of Irish republicanism (9.30 BBC2).
</TEXT>
