<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Patten halts reform tide for schools
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
No more education legislation is planned for England and Wales in the
lifetime of this parliament, Mr John Patten, the education secretary, said
yesterday.
Mr Patten's pledge was interpreted as an attempt to pacify teachers' unions,
which are still considering a boycott of this summer's national curriculum
tests.
He said the legislation to set up a quango for administering teacher
training was 'the last major piece in the jigsaw' of a new settlement for
education which has been introduced by successive acts of parliament since
1988.
Education department officials said several measures to widen the scope of
nursery education would still be possible. But significant changes to the
system controlling primary and secondary schools would not be possible.
The announcement appears to rule out speculation that the government could
force all schools to opt out of local authority control. This would require
primary legislation.
Financial incentives for schools to opt out will be increased, however.
Mr Patten also announced an extension of the government's specialist
colleges plan, which will not be open to local authority schools. He said:
'By the autumn I hope to be in a position to invite bids from those wishing
to set up business and language schools specialising in three or more
foreign languages linked to business studies.'
He said that the scheme, to run on the same lines as the technology colleges
announced earlier this month, would produce 'youngsters able to make the
most of the opportunities offered by the single European market'. Schools
would be required to raise Pounds 100,000 from business sponsors, which
would be matched pound-for-pound by the government.
Mr Patten hopes to invite bids for schools to become specialist sports
colleges at the same time, although business interest has been harder to
define.
Mr Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers reacted angrily. He said: 'It is
profoundly unhelpful to suggest that some schools specialise in languages,
business studies, sports and so forth. All schools should offer these and
other subjects.
The Standing Conference on Schools' Science and Technology launched a scheme
which will aim to help 2,000 primary school teachers each year in teaching
science and technology.
Ciba, the Swiss chemicals company which is underwriting the scheme, said it
was concentrating on primary schools because many teachers were not fully
qualified in science.
</TEXT>
