FT  22 MAR 94 / London post office staff likely to strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Post office counter staff in London look likely to take industrial action
before the end of the month.
Yesterday it was announced they had voted by a three-to-one majority to back
their trade union's call for disruption in protest at main post office
closures.
There was a 45 per cent turnout in the postal ballot called by the Union of
Communication Workers with 664 backing industrial action and 243 voting
against.
The union's executive committee is due to meet today to decide its next
move. Mr Ernie Dudley, the union's national officer for Post Office counter
staff, called on the public to join staff in calling for a halt to closures
and franchising of services in London.
More than 120 main post offices in London have shut since 1989 while across
the country 650 have been cut.
Mr Dudley said the public was suffering from an inferior service as post
office counters were opened in supermarkets.
He said: 'They are putting profit before service. They employ staff who are
inexperienced, poorly trained and badly paid which causes problems and
threatens service quality. These closures are quite simply ripping the heart
out of communities.'
