<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Non-EU trade deficit narrows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK's visible trade deficit with non-European Union countries narrowed to
Pounds 672m in February from a revised Pounds 788m in January. But the
improvement disguised a continued deterioration in trade volumes.
Over the three months to February the volume of UK imports - excluding oil
and erratic items such as aircraft and precious stones - was 3.5 per cent
higher than in the previous three months, while exports rose by only 2 per
cent.
Import volumes in February were the highest ever recorded. The Central
Statistical Office estimates that, on a trend basis, import volumes are
rising by 1 per cent a month while exports are broadly unchanged.
The deterioration in volume terms has been disguised by an improvement in
the terms of trade. British exporters have been increasing their prices
while import prices have been falling.
Over the three months to February, export prices were 7 per cent higher than
in the same three months a year ago, while import prices were 1.5 per cent
lower.
The main reason for the improvement in the headline figure in February was
the oil balance, which improved to a surplus of Pounds 14m from a deficit of
Pounds 75m in January. If oil and erratics are excluded the trade deficit
widened to Pounds 673m in February from Pounds 612m in January.
In the three months to February the deficit, exc-luding oil and erratics,
was Pounds 1.76bn, compared with Pounds 1.71bn in the previous three months.
One encouraging trend is that, according to the CSO, imports of intermediate
and capital goods increased in the three months to February while imports of
consumer goods, excluding cars, fell. This suggests that the rise in imports
is due to manufacturers expanding capacity rather than a consumer boom
sucking in imports.
Mr Kevin Gardiner, UK economist at Morgan Stanley, said the outlook for
exports was relatively bright as world trade grew and Britain remained
competitive.
Figures for trade outside the EU are compiled separately from, and published
earlier than, those for trade with Britain's EU partners.
The EU figures for December were published earlier this month and showed a
sharp deterioration, with a deficit rising to Pounds 903m from Pounds 543m
in November.
The trade figures for the EU are compiled under a new system - Intrastat -
which is based on value added tax, and the statistics are regarded as
unreliable.
