<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Rural stress seen in farmer suicides
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stress, loneliness and de-pression are rife in rural communities and farmers
have one of the highest suicide rates of any occupational group, a
conference in Warwickshire heard yesterday.
The suicide rate among male farmers and farm workers is 187 per million,
compared with the national average of 110 per million. About 39 per cent of
suicides use shotguns or other firearms, easily available on the farm. Only
vets, who often share the rural isolation and have access to drugs, have a
markedly higher level of suicides.
The National Farmers' Union said: 'Farmers are up there with vets, dentists
and pharmacists as the groups having the highest suicide rates.'
The conference on rural stress, organised by a coalition including the NFU,
the Department of Health, the agriculture ministry and the Samaritans, heard
that causes included poor rural services, long working hours, unpredictable
weather and a sense of having little control over the future of the farming
business.
The decline of agriculture has cut the farming workforce by more than half
to 622,000 in the past two decades. The NFU said people were leaving the
land at an average of about 6,000 a year, putting added pressure on those
who remained.
The industry faced further change, with the reform of the Common
Agricultural Policy and the conclusion of a world trade deal likely to lead
to more production cuts and greater rural unemployment.
Public opposition to the set-aside programme, under which Brussels pays
arable farmers to leave some of their land idle to cut overproduction, was
making things worse.
The NFU said: 'They're seen as jolly farmers racing round the countryside in
their Range Rovers not doing very much on the farm, and in most cases
they're saying that's not true. The public doesn't understand the grim
reality of farming.'
The Department of Health is funding a two-year research project by Oxford
University into the causes of rural stress and how it might be eased.
Health professionals will be encouraged to learn more about the problems
facing farming so that they can discuss these when they detect signs of
stress.
</TEXT>
