<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Consumer confidence sinks to four-year low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumer confidence con-tinues to decline as April's tax rises approach and
is at a four-year low, according to a new poll.
Gallup found in its March survey of consumer confidence that 42 per cent of
people think that their household's financial position will deteriorate in
the next 12 months and only 17 per cent think it will improve.
The balance of pessimists over optimists has risen for two successive months
and is at its worst level since April 1990.
Consumers have also become more pessimistic about the prospects for the
economy in general.
While 23 per cent of people think that the economic situation will improve
in the next 12 months, 40 per cent of people say that it will deteriorate.
The negative balance of 17 per cent is the worst since February last year.
People are increasingly concerned about unemployment. The balance of people
expecting a rise in the number of jobless in the next 12 months against
those expecting a decline is 44 per cent, up from 33 per cent in February.
The survey shows more people are thinking of postponing their spending.
Gallup reports that a balance of only 9 per cent of people say that there is
an advantage in making an important purchase now, down from 11 per cent last
month.
Gallup says the survey's findings suggest 'that many people are expecting to
be worse off when the new tax year begins, and this obviously has serious
implications for the strength of economic recovery'.
The report says that next month's survey may show more confidence in the
recovery since February's fall in unemployment was announced too late in
March to influence people's feelings for this month's poll.
The survey of 2,029 people was conducted by Gallup for the European
Commission between March 3 and March 15.
</TEXT>
