<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Calls to backdate change in insolvency law resisted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, ANDREW JACK and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government last night resisted demands for the emergency legislation on
insolvency to be made retrospective to 1986 to safeguard the position of
insolvency practitioners appointed as administrators and receivers to
companies in trouble.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, described as 'speculative'
estimates that practitioners could face claims of up to Pounds 1bn if the
Insolvency (No 2) Bill, which yesterday passed through all its Commons
stages, takes effect only from March 15 1994.
From that date the bill protects administrators and receivers from the
consequences of a Court of Appeal ruling on Paramount Airways which in
effect made them responsible for the contractual employment obligations of a
company after 14 days.
The Confederation of British Industry and the British Bankers' Association
have called in the past few days for the legislation to be made
retrospective as far back as the introduction of the 1986 Insolvency Act.
The latest estimates from the Society of Practitioners of Insolvency suggest
about Pounds 500m could be at stake in additional employment obligations
following the ruling.
Mr Hamilton told MPs it was possible that an appeal against the judgment
could still be considered by the Lords in its judicial capacity. The bill
comes before the Lords today.
He said the government had not been persuaded that the arguments about the
possible liabilities facing accountancy firms justified making the
legislation retrospective to December 31 1986.
Mr Hamilton assured MPs that if developments resulted in the accountants
facing a 'serious problem' the government would be prepared to consider the
matter further.
Mr Stuart Bell, Labour's trade and industry spokesman, said parliament
should use its power to pass retrospective legislation if the original 1986
Insolvency Act, which had given rise to the problem, was shown to be
defective.
Meanwhile, the administrators to Paramount Airways at accountancy firm
Touche Ross are expected to start their appeal to the Lords today. If the
appeal fails practitioners may search for alternative test cases, delaying
further payments to creditors while the position is clarified.
</TEXT>
