<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Rescue plans 'impractical'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government proposals intended to help companies facing financial
difficulties to survive could be counter-productive, the British Bankers'
Association said yesterday.
Mr Brian Pitman, chief executive of Lloyds bank and association
vice-president, said: 'There is a real risk the proposals would work in the
opposite direction.'
The association gave a cautious welcome to the consultation paper on
insolvency when it was published by the Department of Trade and Industry
late last year.
The paper suggested that companies should have a 'breathing space' of 28
days, renewable for up to three months, while they tried to find proposals
acceptable to creditors representing at least 75 per cent of their debts.
Mr Pitman said yesterday legislation that impaired the rights of a bank  -
or another lender which had taken a floating charge - could lead to banks
reducing the amounts they were prepared to lend against stock and debts. He
criticised the proposal under which banks would have to give seven days'
notice of their intention to appoint receivers as 'impractical'.
The association also has reservations about proposals in a DTI consultation
paper on late payment of commercial debt. The paper includes the possibility
of introducing a statutory right to interest on late payment.
The Institute of Directors said a statutory right would alter the behaviour
of companies which found it advantageous to pay after the due date.
But the association doubted whether such an arrangement would work. 'One of
the worries is that in practice many small business would decide it was not
worth the candle, since it would so offend their customers that they could
suffer more,' Mr Pitman said.
</TEXT>
