<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Pension scheme compromise wins support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Proposals aimed at ensuring that occupational pension schemes will not have
to sell equities and buy bonds to meet suggested rules on solvency have won
tentative support from the government.
Actuaries had warned that large-scale withdrawals from equities would have
severely depressed the market.
However, the proposals may require legislation allowing pension scheme
trustees to give members less than their actual accrued benefits if a scheme
is wound up. The proposals broadly follow recommendations from the Institute
and Faculty of Actuaries.
Mr Peter Tompkins, partner at consulting actuaries Lane, Clark and Peacock,
said: 'What lawyers have drawn attention to is that there will be cases
where pension schemes are a bit short.'
But he added that the pensions industry believes a 'watertight' solvency
standard would be far too expensive for employers to bear and would
discourage them from offering final-salary schemes.
The proposals, to be sent today to employer groups such as the Confederation
of British Industry, relate to so-called minimum solvency standards proposed
by the government's Pension Law Review Committee. That committee, chaired by
Professor Roy Goode, proposed that schemes be required to have almost enough
assets so that each member could receive cash to buy out their accrued
benefits.
However, the deferred annuity contracts, which would be used to secure
pension rights in such circumstances, are linked to yields on government
gilts, while the average scheme has about 80 per cent of its assets in
equities.
Because gilts have historically yielded less than equities, pension funds
would have to sell equities and employers would have to top up their cash
position to allow the funds to buy gilts.
Only then could the fund be sure of having enough assets to secure benefits
in the event of wind-up.
The CBI and parts of the pension fund industry have objected to the minimum
solvency proposals since they were made last September, arguing that they
would create an additional burden on employers.
But the actuarial profession has proposed a new way of calculating minimum
solvency. For younger scheme members, actuaries could compute cash
equivalent values assuming investment in equities, and gradually shift
towards gilt yields as employees aged.
The government is suggesting that pension schemes have at least five years
to phase in the solvency rules after an omnibus pension reform bill is
passed, probably next year or in 1996. The government is also prepared to
allow schemes which fall short of the 90 per cent of minimum solvency to
have a longer period in which to add assets to their fund.
The government is considering whether it should set the standards by which
actuaries will calculate minimum solvency or whether it should leave it to
scheme actuaries.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
</TP>
