<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Transport police muddle resolved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fears expressed by Labour MPs that the jurisdiction of British Transport
Police may be curtailed to provide new business for private-sector security
companies were rejected by the government in the Commons last night.
Mr Roger Freeman, public transport minister, insisted that a bill hurriedly
introduced to repair an omission in the legislation privatising British Rail
would ensure that the jurisdiction and powers of the transport police were
unimpaired.
The error arose because the railway privatisation act ignored several
amendments to the act that nationalised the railways which had widened the
powers of transport police.
In effect, the legislation would have allowed transport police to deal with
incidents affecting privatised railway companies but would have prevented
them carrying out further inquiries.
Transport police also warned that the legislation as it stood made it
unclear whether they would have the authority to pursue offenders outside
railway property.
Mr Freeman confirmed that the transport police would have 'complete
jurisdiction' wherever necessary when pursuing a suspect off railway
premises.
The transport police (jurisdiction) bill now goes to the House of Lords.
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow transport secretary, urged the Lords to examine the
bill closely to ensure that it would not lead to more of the railway network
being exempted from coverage by the transport police.
Mr Dobson warned that if the bill resulted in the ending of the transport
police's comprehensive coverage of the rail network it would become more
vulnerable.
He said that the bill had been introduced as an emergency measure because of
'another fine mess' by the government.
Mr Freeman said some 'non-core activities', such as the guarding of freight
depots, might be undertaken by private security companies.
</TEXT>
