<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / MPs to be lobbied on mine pollution
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A cross-party delegation of Durham county councillors will today lobby MPs
and the House of Lords in an attempt to win amendments to the Coal Industry
bill, Chris Tighe writes.
The delegation wants the bill to spell out who will be legally and
financially responsible for minewater pollution, subsidence and methane gas
build-up arising from abandoned and working mines after the industry is
privatised.
The sudden closure of all Durham's remaining pits, removing British Coal's
operational need for minewater pumping, has sparked particular concern in
the county but the issue has implications for other British coalfields.
Bodies including the Country Landowners Association, the National Farmers
Union and the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors have urged the
government to make explicit provision in the bill for the transfer of
environmental liabilities. The government has said it considers the bill as
now drafted to be adequate.
Today's delegation will also press for a commitment from the government that
British Coal and its successor, the Coal Authority, will continue to pump
minewater until a satisfactory solution is achieved, and will be given
adequate government resources to meet environmental responsibilities.
</TEXT>
