<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Industry plans may form Tory agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major has set up a high-level cabinet committee to oversee the
government's planned white paper on competitiveness.
The move has reinforced suggestions in Whitehall that the prime minister
wants the document to become a mid-term manifesto for his government rather
than a more narrow analysis of the immediate problems facing manufacturing
industry.
Mr Major has told colleagues that he intends to make enhancing Britain's
competitive edge a central theme in the second half of the present
parliament.
The white paper will thus be expected to pull together all of the policies
which have an impact on the success of British industry.
Ministers serving on the committee say they plan to combine a detailed
assessment of how British industry is faring on world markets with a much
broader view of the fundamental forces underlying competitiveness.
That implies a reassessment of the government's approach to education and
training; a further drive to encourage the private sector to take on
large-scale infrastructure projects, and a commitment to maintain the pace
of deregulation.
Early drafts circulating to members of the committee also emphasise an
overriding commitment to a stable macro-economic framework and to keeping
business taxes low.
The committee, chaired by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary, is hamstrung to a degree by the Treasury's insistence that the
white paper must not be an excuse for increased public spending.
In spite of his avowed support for the private-sector financing initiative,
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, is being accused by cabinet colleagues of
being over-zealous in his defence of the Treasury's public borrowing rules.
But ministers still see an opportunity in the white paper to give coherence
to a disparate range of policies which have all been aimed at giving support
to manufacturing industry.
Mr Major is particularly keen to see a much closer relationship between the
government's education and training policies with an emphasis on breaking
down the distinctions between academic and vocational qualifications.
Some ministers also want Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, to take
the opportunity to revamp the government's approach to training by
restructuring Training and Enterprise Councils.
For its part, Mr Heseltine's department is examining ways in which the
government can help to build stronger links between industry and the City
and methods of bolstering government support for British exporters.
</TEXT>
