<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / BBC to end Far East TV service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC World Service Television broadcasts from London to northern Asia will
cease in a month under a deal signed yesterday between the BBC and Mr Rupert
Murdoch's News Corporation.
The BBC will give up its broadcasts to north eastern China, Hong Kong,
Taiwan, Korea and Mongolia on the northern beam of the Star TV satellite
system from April 17.
In return Mr Bob Phillis, BBC deputy director-general and chairman of World
Service Television, has negotiated a contract extension to preserve
broadcasts to India, Bangladesh and Pakistan.
Both the BBC and News Corporation had the right to terminate the Star
contract by the end of this year. Mr Murdoch, who bought control of Star
last year, made it clear he wanted the BBC off the system.
The BBC negotiated the compromise in return for vacating early the northern
beam, which Mr Murdoch wants for a Chinese-language film channel aimed at
Taiwan. An announcement on the channel is expected this month.
The BBC will be able to continue broadcasting its news and information
channel on the southern beam until at least the end of March 1996.
No other satellites are available in the region at the moment but the BBC
believes that before March 1996 there could be at least three.
Mr Phillis said yesterday the BBC regretted the withdrawal or contraction of
any service but the agreement with Star TV placed no restriction on the
BBC's future access to the region.
The BBC will now push ahead with plans to launch an Arabic language
satellite service in the Middle East by the autumn. It has also finally
signed a joint venture deal to launch a service in Japan.
Ten thousand BBC technical and production staff are to hold a strike ballot
over proposed changes to working practices and the introduction of
performance-related pay. This follows the breakdown of talks between the
management and broadcasting union Bectu.
</TEXT>
