<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / Sky faces another challenge from pirates
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sky Television is facing another challenge from pirates selling unauthorised
cards to unlock its scrambled subscription channels.
A Bristol-based company is advertising pirate cards which allow viewers to
avoid payment for satellite subscription services such as sport and film
channels. Telephone callers to Euroservices of Kingswood are told that for
Pounds 89.99 an unauthorised card will be provided. This will unlock all
available subscription television channels.
Sky and News Datacom, the 'smart card' decoder company, said in October that
they would pursue pirates in the courts.
A representative of Euroservices said yesterday: 'It's not illegal to sell
the cards. It's not illegal for you to buy them, but it is illegal to use
them. What you do in your own home is your business.'
Under the 1990 Broadcasting Act it is, however, illegal to advertise, sell
or use unauthorised cards. Sky Television - a consortium in which Pearson,
owner of the Financial Times, has a stake - has already taken legal action
against a number of other pirate suppliers.
The Euroservices technical department said that the cards had a detachable
chip. If satellite companies took anti-piracy measures and changed the
broadcast signal a new chip would be sent within three days at no extra
charge. It said the cards were being imported rather than produced locally.
The price of Pounds 89.99 is one of the cheapest on offer so far. Sky
charges Pounds 19.99 a month for a package that includes all its
subscription channels.
European satellite television operators are so concerned about the threat
from pirate cards that they have formed an international group to
co-ordinate counter-measures.
</TEXT>
