<HEADLINE>
FT  22 MAR 94 / S African jail riot kills 21
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Twenty-one prisoners were killed and more than 100 others were injured in
rioting at jails in South Africa yesterday after protests by inmates
demanding voting rights in next month's elections, agencies report from
Johannesburg.
The most serious incident took place in a prison at Queenstown, in the
Eastern Cape, where 21 prisoners suffocated after setting their communal
cell ablaze.
More than 2,000 prisoners went on the rampage at Pietermaritzburg prison, in
Natal, and prisons spokesman, Colonel Barry Eksteen, said warders fired
teargas in an attempt to control the inmates. He said some 120 people were
injured.
Prisoners on death row at Pretoria jail also joined the protest, setting 18
cells alight, and destroying bedding and furniture. The authorities gave no
details of casualties.
</TEXT>
