FT  21 MAR 94 / Observer: Peer pressure
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Say what you will about Sir John Banham, the former director general of the
CBI, he keeps rattling the establishment cage. His criticisms of the way
Britain is run in his new book, Anatomy of Change, will not endear him to
Whitehall mandarins, and he has not made his chairmanship of the Local
Government Commission any easier by highlighting the Government's own
inability to make up its mind.
Given that Sir John has just added the chairmanship of Tarmac to his growing
portfolio of directorships, he could be forgiven for wanting to lighten his
load of public duties in order to concentrate on his business career.
However, Sir John's job of reviewing local government is only halfway
through and he insists he has every intention of staying on until the task
is finished in about a year's time.
That sort of devotion to public duty is surely worth a peerage. Will it be
Lord Banham of Avon, covering Gloucestershire, Somerset and Bristol, or Lord
Banham of Centrepoint?
