<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / R-R to buy Pounds 14m computer design system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rolls-Royce will announce today the largest order ever placed by a UK
engineering company for computer-aided design and manufacturing systems as
part of its efforts to improve the design and production of jet engines.
The UK aero-engine and industrial power group is buying Pounds 14m worth of
CAD/CAM software and services for its aero-engine division from
Computervision, the US software house.
Computervision said the initial order from Rolls-Royce involved 1,000
terminals or design stations. The company added that the aero-engine
manufacturer had an option to buy and install a further 1,000 terminals by
the end of the decade.
According to the US company the order is potentially worth more than Pounds
40m over seven years.
Rolls-Royce's CAD/CAM investment reflects a growing trend in the aerospace
industry, with manufacturers increasingly turning to computer systems to
help them design and test products before they are manufactured, to reduce
production lead times and reduce the risk of malfunctions and other teething
problems.
Airframe manufacturers such as Boeing of the US and the European Airbus
consortium have used CAD/CAM to design what they call 'paperless' aircraft
to enhance the development of complex aircraft programmes.
Rolls-Royce Aeroengines in Derby has already spent Pounds 10m over the past
five years installing about 700 Unix CAD workstations.
Rolls-Royce will eventually be able to design and develop paperless jet
engines with its software. The new system will make it possible to design,
'build' and prove jet engines electronically before any metal or composites
are cut.
The two companies also say they are entering into a strategic relationship.
Mr Phil Ruffles, director of engineering of Rolls-Royce's aerospace group,
said: 'Our new joint approach is a departure from the traditional
supplier-customer relationship and is one that I believe other industries
will have to consider in the near future.'
</TEXT>
