<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / Review of dentists' pay likely to propose shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government plans to publish a long-awaited consultation paper this week
which is likely to include proposals for restructuring of the dental health
service.
The Department of Health confirmed yesterday that it would probably publish
on Thursday its first public response to the review of dentists'
renumeration by Sir Kenneth Bloomfield, the former head of the Civil Service
in Northern Ireland.
Dr Brian Mawhinney, health minister, said the delay in publishing the green
paper had come about mainly because of the lack of consensus in and outside
the dental profession about how to make the service more cost-effective.
Under the options presented by Sir Kenneth, reforms might include limiting
treatment available under the health service, or restricting eligibility for
free or subsidised dental care. The report favours keeping free treatment
for children, but not necessarily for all pregnant women.
Options put forward by Sir Kenneth include relatively minor changes. The
government is believed to favour more radical reform, although it has not
ruled out returning to free dental checks. Some dentists and doctors have
claimed a rise in avoidable deaths from oral cancer since their abolition
four years ago.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour's health spokesman, predicted that the government
plans were 'worse' that reports suggested, and that a 'hidden agenda'
included denying free provision to pregnant women.
He said yesterday: 'My feeling is that the government is moving into charges
as an alternative to taxes.'
Mr Michael Watson of the British Dental Association said yesterday he
thought it likely that the government would lay out options and delay final
decisions on the scope and funding of NHS dentistry.
He said: 'We want a service that is clearly targeted where it is needed most
and not just making it easier for the well off.'
</TEXT>
