FT  21 MAR 94 / RJB set to reopen S Yorkshire pit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A former British Coal pit is to be reopened by RJB Mining, in a move that is
set to create 120 mining jobs.
British Coal is poised to confirm today that it has reached terms for the
leasing of Rossington colliery near Doncaster in South Yorkshire, which
closed last April with the loss of 500 jobs, to the company.
RJB has already reopened Clipstone colliery in Nottinghamshire, which was
also recently closed by British Coal, and has expressed interest in a number
of other deep mines.
After today's formal hand-over, Mr Richard Budge, chief executive of RJB, is
thought likely to double the Rossington workforce to about 250 when the pit
is in full production.
Up to 10 former British Coal pits could reopen under private management
before the industry is privatised later this year.
Betws colliery in south Wales is set to be taken over by a management
buy-out team, and Mr Malcolm Edwards, the former British Coal commercial
director, hopes to restart production soon at Trentham in Staffordshire and
Coventry in the Midlands.
