<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / Easing of curbs on migrants is urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Immigration restrictions are depriving UK businesses of much-needed
professional and managerial skills, says a report published today by the
left-of-centre Institute for Public Policy Research.
The institute says that changes in immigration policy could bring economic
benefits in the form of skilled labour and an inflow of investors and
entrepreneurs from overseas.
Any such change would also help in attracting international companies by
making it easier for them to transfer staff to the UK.
The report points out that other western countries actively promote
immigration to fill skill shortages and boost their economies. Britain's
policy on migrants was adopted in the 1960s to deal with large-scale
immigration to fill low-skill jobs. It neglects the needs of the labour
market for selective, skilled immigration, and erects unnecessary barriers
to entrepreneurs who would invest in the UK and create jobs.
The institute says the work-permit system operates primarily as a form of
entry control, rather than a system for identifying the UK's economic needs
for migrants. It should be revised to adapt to current migration and
economic conditions.
The UK approach is contrasted with those of the US, Canada and Australia,
where immigration is seen as a means of attracting people who can contribute
to economic growth.
The report says substantial numbers of migrants are unlikely to be needed to
fill UK labour shortages. Relaxation of immigration policy is necessary,
however, in a world where certain types of human capital have become much
more mobile.
Strangers &amp; Citizens. IPPR, 30 Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA. Pounds
14.95.
</TEXT>
