<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / Insolvency ruling could spark 'crippling' claims
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Accountancy firms could face claims of up to Pounds 1bn from people who have
lost their jobs over the past seven years, the Confederation of British
Industry warned yesterday.
This follows a recent Appeal Court ruling which suggested that
administrators were deemed to have adopted the contractual employment
obligations of a company after 14 days.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, said claims could arise in cases
where it was eventually found impossible to keep companies afloat.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, moved quickly after the
ruling because accountants acting as receivers said they could not produce a
rescue package within 14 days and would be forced to sack everyone in all
cases to avoid claims.
Emergency legislation to clarify the employment obligations of companies in
receivership is due to go through the House of Commons today. It will state
that if there have been no new employment contracts agreed after 14 days of
the receivership or administration of a company, only wages, salaries and
pensions contributions will rank as secured creditors.
The CBI warned yesterday that unless the changes in the Insolvency Act were
made retrospective accountancy firms could be put out of business as a
result of claims made on them.
Mr Davies said: 'Claims are most likely from directors and senior
management. The directors of Olympia &amp; York (developers of Canary Wharf) are
already reported to have lodged claims totalling Pounds 10m.'
Mr Davies said many businesses depended on the availability of services from
medium-sized accountancy firms. He added: 'It is of great concern that such
firms now face the possibility of crippling claims and of going under
themselves.'
</TEXT>
