<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / Easing of media stake rules urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Four of the UK's biggest newspaper groups have told the government that the
rules on cross-media ownership must be rescinded if Britain is to take
advantage of the multimedia revolution.
According to the British Media Industry Group, which includes Associated
Newspapers, Telegraph Publishing, the Guardian Media Group and Pearson,
owner of the Financial Times, the UK rules are the most restrictive in
Europe.
Under the 1990 Broadcasting Act newspapers are limited to one 20 per cent
stake in television companies followed by further stakes of no more than 5
per cent.
The group says in its submission to the cross-media ownership review by the
National Heritage department that the restrictions need to be abolished to
give publishers the right to diversify 'into the new multinational and
multimedia market'.
The group says that newspapers and other forms of publishing are in
long-term decline compared with the rest of the media marketplace.
The Independent Television Commission said in its submission to the
department that newspapers should be able to have larger stakes in
television companies but that the limit should stay below 30 per cent, at
least for the time being.
</TEXT>
