<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / Dreams of striking up the band: The plans of managers at
South West Trains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The opportunity to earn 'rail miles' on petrol purchases, the sale of rail
tickets through cut-price 'bucket shops' and an introductory free
rail-travel scheme are proposed by South West Trains once British Rail is
privatised.
Mr Peter Cotton, commercial director of South West, a division of BR's
Network SouthEast, said innovative marketing would be one of the methods
used to attract people to the railways.
South West runs trains from London Waterloo to Reading, Exeter, Weymouth and
Portsmouth.
Mr Cotton, formerly managing director of Del Monte UK, said: 'Commuters
often feel they are a captive market. We need to do more for them. It sounds
frivolous but we might have a silver band playing in the station at
Christmas.'
Mr Peter Field, managing director, said senior managers of South West were
'seriously interested' in launching a buy-out bid for their company,
probably late next year. The managers hope that they can obtain a franchise
for 15 to 20 years, longer than has been indicated by the government. South
West has a turnover of Pounds 230m and employs more than 4,000 people.
The potential for increasing the number of passengers from the present
280,000 a week is large. Sixty per cent of adults in the south-east of
England never travel by rail, 30 per cent use trains infrequently for
leisure travel and 4 per cent commute daily.
Mr Field said: 'We are fishing in a big pool. We need to get people to try
us by, for example, providing more information for non-regular users.'
He said the smaller, franchised railway companies would be able to take
greater account of local needs than was possible in BR.
South West is working with local councils and with Railtrack, the company
which will own BR's track, on proposals to build a line to link Heathrow
airport to the main line to Waterloo.
It has plans for a fast shuttle service between Waterloo and Southampton,
running air-conditioned trains at 20-minute intervals.
Mr Field said fears that rail franchisees would have difficulty raising
finance appeared unfounded. 'We have had serious expressions of interest
from venture capitalists and from potential trade partners,' he added.
South West has ambitious diversification plans. It would like to acquire its
own maintenance facilities, handle its own advertising activities and manage
retail outlets on stations.
Mr Field said: 'British Rail could not do this because it was focused on
cutting costs.'
</TEXT>
