<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / Schools criticise council review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Schools and their governors have launched a campaign against the English
local government review. They believe it will create weak, unnecessarily
expensive education authorities, staffed by inexperienced officers.
The government will be concerned as this suggests that not only heads but
also parents and governors, given more power recently, oppose the review. A
coalition of educational interest groups last year forced national
curriculum changes.
Mr Peter Downes, vice-president of the Secondary Heads Association, received
loud applause from the association's annual conference when he told Mr John
Patten, education secretary: 'We are very firmly of the opinion that the
two-tier system works pretty well as far as education (the biggest part of
local government services) is concerned, and we think that the prospect of
spending Pounds 1.5bn in transitional costs to produce a new structure which
would arguable be worse than what we have got at the moment is nothing short
of a scandalous waste of public money.'
The review, being carried out by the Local Government Commission, aims to
produce plans for a local government structure for all of non-metropolitan
England this year. Education, now a county council function, would be
transferred to smaller single-tier authorities.
The National Association of Governors and Managers predicted that schools
would 'hardly take kindly to being run by inexperienced administrators' with
small budgets.
</TEXT>
