FT  21 MAR 94 / Talk Radio aims for year-two profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Talk Radio UK, the highest bidder in the tenders for Britain's first
national commercial radio licence, says it will break into profit in its
second year on-air.
The company bid Pounds 3.8m a year for its licence, more than Pounds 1m a
year more than its nearest rival Newstalk UK, a consortium led by Associated
Newspapers, publisher of the Daily Mail. Talk Radio UK will be awarded its
licence by June or July as long as the Radio Authority is convinced of its
business plan.
Mr Christopher Turner, a director of media investment fund Media Ventures,
which has a 31 per cent stake in Talk Radio, denies allegations from rivals
and some advertising specialists that Talk Radio's bid is too high for its
format to sustain. If the Radio Authority were to judge that the bid was not
viable, the licence would pass to Newstalk UK.
Mr Turner said yesterday: 'This isn't a potty scheme. It's been thoroughly
thought through.' The company is expected to spend Pounds 12m in its first
year with a loss of Pounds 1m and then move into profit.
Talk Radio is planning to have only 50 permanent staff with presenters, many
of them journalists, on contracts.
