<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / Fate of Dollars 600m Bulgarian loan deal in balance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SOFIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The future of a Dollars 600m (Pounds 401m) International Monetary Fund and
World Bank loan package, aimed to help Bulgaria settle its Dollars 9.3bn
debt to the London Club of commercial banks, may be settled at a meeting of
European Union finance ministers in Brussels today.
The ministers are due to consider Bulgaria's request for Dollars 330m in
balance of payments support for 1994 from the G24 group of countries.
The positive response would enable the IMF to go ahead with new stand-by
loans and funds designed to help the reform worth Dollars 400m. It would
also unlock Dollars 200m in linked World Bank loans.
The IMF cannot agree the loan unless Bulgaria has the necessary financial
support needed to implement the economic reform programme it agreed with the
Fund last December.
Foreign financing is needed if Bulgaria is to meet its June 30 deadline to
reschedule its Dollars 9.3bn foreign commercial debt. Under a framework
agreement reached last November, the London Club banks chaired by Deutsche
Bank, agreed to halve the debt. In return, Bulgaria said it would pay
Dollars 850m immediately if it could get IMF and World Bank backing.
Bulgarian officials say it is essential that G24 agrees the funding without
delay because of the severe devaluation of the leva. The currency has lost
25 per cent of its value in the last month, making the 1994 budget
unrealistic.
'Everything will fall apart if we do not get support from the G24. Otherwise
we will have to renegotiate a whole new package with the IMF and the World
Bank which could take months,' Mr Dimitar Kostov, deputy finance minister,
said in an interview.
Bulgaria is the last former East Bloc country (outside the former Soviet
Union) with unresolved foreign commercial debt.
Foreign investment, needed to finance the country's transition to a market
economy, is not expected to pick up until the debt is settled. According to
official figures, Bulgaria had attracted only Dollars 220m in foreign funds
by the end of 1993, a fraction of the amount committed to other central
European countries.
</TEXT>
