<HEADLINE>
FT  21 MAR 94 / US to seek UN backing over North Korea inspections
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US is to seek United Nations support in an attempt to force North Korea
to allow international inspectors full access to its nuclear facilities, it
said yesterday.
Washington said it was also ready to act bilaterally, increasing its
military activities in the region. Mr Warren Christopher, US secretary of
state, said the US was preparing to deploy Patriot missiles in South Korea
and to reinstate joint military exercises with South Korea 'in the very near
future'.
'We're not seeking a confrontation with North Korea, but if they insist on
it, I'm sure we'll prevail,' Mr Christopher said on US television.
Mr Christopher said the US would be seeking a resolution at the UN Security
Council. 'I think we'll be preparing for trade sanctions,' Mr Christopher
added, but this depended on North Korea's actions.
Congressional leaders put their weight behind the administration's increased
pressure. Congressman Richard Gephardt, the House majority leader, said US
aircraft carriers would be despatched to the region unless Pyongyang
complied with inspectors from the International Atomic Energy Agency. The US
may also increase its troop strength there, he added. Currently 37,000 US
troops are stationed in South Korea.
The board of governors for the IAEA is expected to decide today to refer the
North Korean nuclear issue to the Security Council.
In Beijing yesterday, Chinese leaders told Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, the
visiting Japanese prime minister, they would try to persuade North Korea to
open its nuclear sites to avoid an international crisis, but Beijing
counselled patience.
China is key to any international approach. If China blocks sanctions in the
UN Security Council, the US and South Korea will have few options left,
short of military actions, to force the north to accept nuclear inspections.
Mr Christopher said China would support the US plan because it was in its
own interest to do so. 'They are much closer at hand than we are.'
However, China's ambassador to South Korea warned at the weekend that his
country would not support sanctions against the north. 'Such measures are
not only ineffective, but would also complicate matters and aggravate the
situation,' Mr Zhang Tingyan, the Chinese ambassador, told the South Korean
news agency Yonhap.
Any military response, such as an air strike on the North's nuclear
facilities, is considered unlikely, however, since it would almost certainly
provoke a North Korean attack on the South and destabilise the north-east
Asian region.
Beijing promises to work on Pyongyang, Page 2
</TEXT>
