<HEADLINE>
FT  19 MAR 94 / Palestinians expected to join resumed Middle East peace
talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS at the UN, New York
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Palestine Liberation Organisation and three Arab states are expected to
resume stalled peace talks with Israel soon, Mr Warren Christopher, the US
secretary of state, said in Washington last night.
He said Lebanon, Jordan and Syria had agreed to resume talks with Israel
next month and this would provide 'a strong impetus' to the PLO to return to
the bargaining table and to conclude arrangements for Palestinian self-rule
in Jericho and Gaza.
The announcement came immediately after the United Nations security council
passed a resolution condemning the Hebron massacre and urged an
international presence in the region. The PLO had linked resuming
negotiations with Israel to passage of the resolution.
The PLO abandoned Middle East peace talks last month after an Israeli
settler killed about 30 Palestinians at a mosque in the West Bank town of
Hebron, saying it wanted the ejection of rightwing settlers and protection
for Palestinians.
'There have been intensive Israel-Palestinian contacts at the highest levels
today including a telephone call between prime minister Rabin and chairman
Arafat,' Mr Christopher said.
Mr Yassir Arafat, the PLO chairman, is expected to meet Mr Shimon Peres, the
Israeli foreign minister, in Cairo early next week in an attempt to clear
the way for a resumption of negotiations on Palestinian autonomy in the
occupied territories.
Mr Peres said yesterday he planned to discuss with Mr Arafat ways to speed
up the implementation of the 'Gaza-and-Jericho first' autonomy.
Israel's meeting with PLO representatives would focus on security measures
in the West Bank and the likely resumption of full-scale peace negotiations.
US Middle East co-ordinator Mr Dennis Ross would be travelling to the region
'in the next few days for additional consultations with the parties'.
In Israel, speculation intensified yesterday that the government was
considering evacuating some of the settler enclaves in the heart of Hebron.
</TEXT>
<XX>
